    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start. My students might ask why this is such a big deal if the Constitution doesn't actually list all these rights explicitly. Could you expand on that part? Like, how does the idea of \"fundamental liberties\" work if they aren't written in the text? Can you show how this doctrine is basically the most important way we protect modern rights?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The concept of \"fundamental liberties\" is rooted in the inherent dignity of the individual, which the Founders understood as a bedrock principle of American liberty, even if they didn't list every modern right. Substantive due process acts as the necessary bulwark against government overreach, ensuring that the Constitution remains a living document protecting human rights against legislative whim. Without this doctrine, the government could easily erode personal freedoms simply by passing laws that are technically legal but morally oppressive. It is the ultimate check on governmental power to preserve the core of American freedom.",
      "source": "target",
